29, 30. Uswpatur,idem jus, vi adempta. “ The same (constitutional) form of authority is observed, its efficacy (however) having been taken away.” In the fifth century of the city the change began. By one of the laws of the plebeian dictator, Q. Publilius Philo, it was enacted (Liv. viii„ 12) that in the case of laws to be enacted at the comitia centuriata, the fathers should give their assent before the vote of the comitia centuriata was taken. By a lex Moenia, of uncertain date (Cic., Brut„ c. 14), the same change was made as to elections which the Publilia lex had made as to the enacting of laws. This will serve to explain the language of Livy in the text.—In incertam even- tum, etc. ‘⁶ The fathers give their sanction with respect to the un- certain issue of the comitia‚'’ i. e.‚ to the decision of the comitia, be- fore it has been made, and while it is still uncertain what that decision will be.
